What is Policy Brand? (Part 1)

An overview of Policy Brands Roundtables research model and its development

by: DCypher

With the decline of tenure for Congressional members and staff, the adoption of new technologies within government, and expectations of data-driven decision-making, there is a striking new importance of developing image, profile, and sentiment. This image is not necessarily the corporations consumer-facing image, but whats called the organizations policy brand. Policy brand refers to the way senior policy professionals perceive an organizations work inside the Beltway-specifically, the degree to which it compels attention and action on matters of national public policy.

Synopsis

Policy Brands Roundtable (PBR) is National Journal Researchs strategic research initiative designed to understand the perceptions of Washington influentials and their views on the major organizations, industies, and players relevant their policy expertise area.

The model that PBR is built on revolves around 16 metrics (called drivers) that measure an organization performance on the distinct roles, attributes, and the visible activities related to government affairs. The model then compares the performance on these metrics against the perception of the organization evaluated against 4 index metrics.

After rigorously testing of more than 70 different test metrics over the course of two years, this model was developed, and the first installment of the full study was launched in the fall of 2013. Our ongoing research is currently (Spring 2015) on its fourth installment and continues to futher the understanding of the relationship and engagement among organizations and policy makers.

This article will focus on the two years leading up to our first full launch. It will provide a detailed overview of the research model that PBR currently uses to capture policy brand, and describe the major processes and analysis that led up to its conception.

The Goal of Testing

Over the course of two years, partnering with APCO International, National Journal Research conducted three major rounds of studies that were precursors to the Policy Brands Roundtable innitiative. These precursors sought to answer two questions: 1) Which organizational activities do policy influentials care most about? and 2) How is an individuals perception of an organizations policy work shaped?

The first round of testing, we conducted over 380 in depth interviews with policy influentials to try to find out what influentials care about. Based on these interviews, our previous Best Practice research, and other various research studies, we innitially identified around 50 core activies and 6 measures of perception.

While there could be many different roles and duties of an organizations government affairs office, not all of them directly affect their policy brand. For example, an organization could be timely bill payers, always paying their vendors on time or in advance. While this might contribute to an efficencient office, which in turn might enhances their ability to lobby effecitvely, this activity would be an example of something that has a very indirect affect on policy perception. Therefore, Timely Vendor Payment would not be within the model.

The challenge is narrowing down from the 50+ core activities identified to ones with the most directly impact policy perception. Hence, goal of this whole process is to reduce the dimentiality of the data so that with only a small number of variables we are able to capture just as much information about policy brand perception as with 50+ variables.

First Round of Testing

In the first round of testing, we conducted a test survey on a sample of influentials measuring their perception of different organizations and asking each respondent to rate those organizations on the various activities we identified.

The data collected for this study is in the file named: AsoRep pre launch 7_28_15 BLIND.csv.

Using a series of factor analyses, network modeling, and cluster analyses, we attempted to model the relationship among these variables. This is a visualization of cluster analysis that was used to inform the finding:

The 56 variables represent the individual ratings that the respondents gave on the corresponding survey question. For example the survey text for the variable Consideration reads: Do you genuinely consider [the organization]s positions on issues?

For the full list of cooresponding survey question text, refer to the file AsoRep study question text Meta.csv.

From our analysis, the 50+ variables generally cluster around 9 catagories: Consideration, Sharing, Industry Stewardship, Subject Matter Contribution, Organizational Visibility, Policy Positioning, External Engagement, Leadership and Governance, and Lobbying Activity.

The consideration and sharing catagories are index variables they represent the components of the individuals perception of the organization as a whole rather than specific activities.

The variables in the Consideration cluster are all questions related to whether the respondent takes into account of the opinions of a particular organization when making policy decisions. Sharing seems to be a cluster of variables related to whether the respondent will perform some action on behalf of the organization such as disseminate its material, seek out its opinion, or recommend its staff.

The remaining catagories are driver variables - these variables measure the specific activities that organizations engage in that we identified in our interviews. This is a broad description of what each of these catagory clusters seem to relate to:

  • Industry Stewardship - these drivers are related to an organizations ability to lead, manage, and regulate the members of the industry that it belongs to.

  • Subject Matter Contribution - these drivers have to do with the organizations ability to produce and disseminate quality and pertinate research and information to aid the policy makers in that space.

  • Organization Visibility - are a cluster of measures that relate to the ability to gain and retain public attention or attention on their issues.

  • Policy Positioning - refer to a driver cluster that speak to the organizations tactics and strategy in manuvering through the polical process during policy fights.

  • External Engagement - contain measures related to an organizations ability to rally support and build alliances.

  • Leadership and Governance - this cluster speak to the organizations influence on government as a whole and at the various levels of government.

  • Lobbying Ability - this cluster relates to the organizations ability to build and leverages those internal relationships to move the levers of government.

In this round of tests we followed a similar process as the first round. A couple of the highlighted observations that came out of the first two rounds of testing are:

  • The Consideration and Sharing clusters are quite different from the other groups, as should be expected since they capture perception of an organization as a whole.

  • There are certain variables like Bipartisan Cooperation and Bipartisan Favorability or Industry Ambassador and Industry Voice that are so connected that it might be justified to combine them into one variable.

  • Then there are variables that seem out of place and unconnected with the other variables, that we either kept for further testing or dropped because that particular variable has very little direct impact on policy perception, upon further analysis.

  • The relationship between the variables within Lobbying Ability" and Leadership and Governance are so interconnected that they can be combined into one cluster.

Third Round of Testing

In the third round of testing we tested another subset of 37 variables. A couple key differences between this study and the previous two are:

  • We asked respondents to evaluate only corporations, whereas the previous two tests consisted of only associations.

  • Certain variables were excluded since corporations did not engage in those activities. These were primarily member related and the industy stewardship variables that are only relevant to associations.

  • Additional variables were added that only applied to corporations such as the corporate citizenship driver measures. Also, several additional index measures were introduced that originated in National Journals 2011 Best Brands study. The Best Brands study was an extensive research innitiative that looked at the respected corporate brands in DC at the time. The variables added to this round of testing from the Best Brands included: Respect, Integrity, Influence, Personal Lobbyist, Agreement.

The results of the third round of study were for the most part consistent with the previous two. The main finding is that there seems to be six clusters of drivers that emerged, four of which are nearly identical to the ones in previous rounds. The other two are characterized as follows:

  • Corporate citizenship - which consisted of the measures related to a companys adherence to ethical responsibilities.

  • Lobbying Expertise - which is the Lobbying Ability" cluster and Leadership Governance clusters combined. As shown in the previous two tests the variables in these clusters are so interconnect that they can really be thought of as part of one group.

The last round of studies also seems to reveal that there are 4 components of policy brand perception: Respect, Influence, Sharing, and Consideration. More on this later.

Developing the Model

Again, the end goal of the entire process is to eliminate variables. We want to capture every possible dimention that impacts perception with as few variables as possible. After conducting these three rounds of testing, we took a wholelistic view of the process in narrowing down our final set of measures. The following are the criterion we used:

  1. Criteria of Similarity

Within each of the clusters, we analyzed the variables that were highly related with each other, these variables were either combined or eliminated.

For example, Industry Enforcer reads: enforces industry codes of conduct among its members and Industry Conduct Adherance reads: promotes high standards in the industry it represents by establishing and adhering to industry codes of conduct. Its not particularily supprising that they turned out to be highly correlated in the data (Graphic 1). Intuitively, organizations which enforce codes of conduct are also the ones that promotes and adheres to those conducts. Hence, these two variables were combined to form Industy Standards, which read: promotes high standards by establishing and enforcing industry practices, standards, and/or codes of conduct.

With the same analyses, we also concluded that certain variables could be eliminated all together because they were already captured by another variable or they could be imputed by another variable. As an example, Interest Group Relations was eliminated because its highly correlated with Coalition Building. Both of these variables are trying to capture the organizations ability to create and join factions with other groups, but Coalition Building is a bit more broad where as Interest Group Relations focuses on interest groups in particular. Hence, we decided to eliminate Interest Group Relations for Coalition Building.

  1. Criteria of Difference

For variables that were highly related with the rest of the other variables, we either investigated further or removed them. The highly unrelated variables, for the most part, are ones that were poorly written questions or so specific or specialized that it did not make sense to use them in the prediction model.

An example of this is the variable Personal Lobbyist, which reads: [organization] has a lobbyist (or other staff resource) whom I know and can call upon if I have questions. Our research interviews have shown that having personal connection can positively shape an individuals views of an organization. However, an organization can only make so many personal connections, certainly not enough to make an impact on the organizations overall policy perception.

The fear with eliminating variables based on difference is the danger that the variable in question actually belongs to a cluster catagory that was not captured by the exsiting data. In essence, there may be overarching catagories of activities which impact policy perception, but we have failed to capture because the variables in our study is not complete.

Incomplete information is always a legitimate concern in research studies. The way we address this issue is through dudiligence in identifying our core variables in the first place. Dudilligence in conducting nearly 400 in depth interviews with policy makers to compile our core variables. If our comilation of variables is complete, clusters that emerged from these variables should be comprehensive. Hence, variables that have weak relationships with any of the existing clusters are more likely to be arbitritions rather than belonging to another relevant cluster catagory not captured by the model.

  1. Criteria of Confoundment

The next layer of analysis was looking confounding variables. These variables were either so out of place in the cluster that they were placed in or overly correlated with too many different variables. These variables tended to be questions that were poorly written or overly broad, in wich case should be eliminated. In a small number of cases, after further investgatigation, they were recatagoriezed.

A good example a confounding variable is Multilateral Impact, which reads [the organization] works effectively across the executive, legislative, and regulatory branches. In both the rounds of testing that contained this variable, the data showed that it suffered from a high degree of multi-colinearity. This question is simply too broad. Its essentially just asking about general effectiveness, since effective organizations typically are effective across all branches rather than being effective in one branch, but not another. Further, it doesnt address any specific activity that the organization does; just asks about the general ability of the organization to impact government. Hence, it is a confounding variable in the model and was eleminated.

  1. Criteria of Importance

The last layer of analysis we used is evaluating the improtance of each variable in the model. The analysis we used is a method known as the relative weights analysis. Part two of this model overview will go over this method in much more detail, but here is a short explaination:

The general idea of this method is to determine each variables reletive level of contribution to the predictiveness of a multi-variate regression. To elaborate, the driver measures can be thought of as regressor variables in a regression, because they attempt to predict the criterion variable, policy brand perception. The r-squared value reflects the precentage that the regressors (drivers) explain the dependent variable (brand perception). The relative weights method allow us to measure, for each regressor, its relative contribution to that explainability. The higher the relative weight, the more it contributes to the regressions predictiveness and the important the regressor variabe is to the regression model.

One question that seems naturally to follow is: if the drivers are the independent variables, and policy brand perception is the dependent variable in the regression, how exactly is policy brand perception calculated? This, again, will be explored in depth in part two of this model overview. As for now, the short answer is: by combining index variables. The index variables are what we have identified to be the components of policy brand perception. Hence, we used a similar statistical method to develop a composite variable, made up of the final index measures, to represent policy brand perception. Much more on this in part 2.

Final Measures Developed

As mentioned in the begining, these tests are designed to answer two questions: 1) Which organizational activities policy do influentials care most about? and 2) How is an individuals perception of an organizations policy work shaped?

The following is the final variable set and a visualization of the dimention reduction path for which each was developed.

The answer to the first question is: we have narrowed it down to these 9 activities relevant to both corporation and assocations:

  • Bipartisan Collaboration - [The organizations ability to] work collaboratively with policy leaders across the political spectrum.

  • Constructive Arguments - [The organization ability to] provide powerful, constructive arguments that engage peers and advance relevant policy discourse.

  • Compromise - [The organization ability to] negotiate for consensus; balances different views and make reasonable trade-offs on tough issues.

  • Coalition Building - [The organization ability to] develop meaningful coalitions with credible partner organizations and thought leaders.

  • Relevance - [The organization ability to] contextualize its policy positions in relevant terms [and] quantif[y] the effects of its positions.

  • Grassroots - [The organization ability to gain] active support by individual stakeholders (employees, members, and/or the public) who directly contact policy leaders to advance the organizations priorities.

  • Research - [The organization ability to] contribute accurate and reliable new research and data that help to inform policy development.

  • Lobbying Representation - [The organization] has effective lobbying representation; [the ability to] build and maintain direct relationships with policymakers, regulators, and other key individuals.

  • Media Profile - [The organization ability to] successfully leverages media to communicate information about the organization and its policy issues.

Graphic 5: Final Driver Set Developed After 3 Rounds of Studies (pg.1)

Graphic 6: Final Driver Set Developed After 3 Rounds of Studies (pg.2)

In addition, we identified 3 actions unique to corporations:

  • C-Suite Engagement - [The organizations ability to] effectively involve its senior-most business executives (e.g.the CEO) in Washington discussions.

  • Ethics - [The organizations ability to] stand for sound ethics, conduct and accountability in its business operations.

  • CSR - [The organizations ability to] demonstrate [a] commitment to furthering meaningful social responsibility.

We also identified 3 actions unique to associations:

  • Industry Standards - [The organization ability to] promote high standards by establishing and enforcing industry practices, standards and/or codes of conduct.

  • Unified Voice - [The organization ability to] represent the voice of the entire industry and/or the interests of all its members to external stakeholders.

  • Events - [The organization ability to] sponsor events and conferences that add its perspective to the policy dialogue.

Graphic 7: Final Driver Set Developed After 3 Rounds of Studies (pg.3)

The answer to the second question is: perception of an organizations policy brand consists of 4 components. The are as follows:

  • Respect - []respect for [the organizations] role in the public debate?

  • Considetation - []genuine consideration [of the organizations] positions on issues?

  • Influence - [organizations] views influencing [policy makers] views favorably?

  • Sharing - [the willingness of the policy maker to ] seek out or share the organizations opinion on issues

Graphic 8: Final Index Measures Developed after 3 Rounds of Studies
